  "opinion": "As a transgender woman who’s been working as a barista in Rome for over thirty years, I’ve seen how science can feel like a distant world from everyday life. The gender gap in science isn’t just about numbers—it’s about who gets to feel seen and heard. When I talk to my clients, they often mention how their kids’ school projects on physics or biology feel disconnected from real life. I’ve noticed that in my community, especially among women and non-binary folks, there’s a quiet frustration with how science is taught in a way that doesn’t reflect diverse perspectives. For me, this gap isn’t just a problem of representation—it’s a problem of belonging. My own journey has been shaped by the fact that I was raised in a family where education wasn’t always the priority, but I’ve learned to value curiosity and critical thinking through my work with children. I believe we should address the gender gap in science because it’s about creating spaces where everyone feels they can contribute without fear. How? By making science more relatable, starting with local contexts like the rivers and mountains of Rome, or even the way people interact in cafes. It’s not about changing the science itself, but about changing how it’s presented so that it feels relevant to all. This isn’t just a theoretical issue—it’s about ensuring that the next generation doesn’t have to look up to someone else to understand the world. As someone who’s anxious about fitting in, I know that when people feel they don’t belong, they stop trying. So, yes, we should address it, and we should do it by making science feel like a conversation that happens in the same room as your daily life.",
